title: For Sale:  8" Rifle Solvent Trap (that can be modified to become a) Suppressor Silencer Aluminum
postcontent: You are purchasing a SOLVENT TRAP for rifles that can be modified to become a legal suppressor (silencer)Machined to fit perfectly in USA by a veteran. Very precise measurements that are much, much better than the typical solvent trap, or maglight make-shift suppressor.These can be Cerakoted to your liking if you find that necessary.1/2-28 threadYou will need a drill press to modify this into a suppressor***ONLY do so if legal in your state, AND you are legally allowed to have a suppressor and only AFTER you get the tax stamp from the ATF***---Why you should suppress your firearm---HEARING PROTECTIONSuppressors reduce the noise of a gunshot by an average of 20 – 35 dB, which is roughly the same as earplugs or earmuffs. By decreasing the overall sound signature, suppressors help to preserve the hearing of recreational shooters, hunters, and hunting dogs around the world.SAFER HUNTINGMost hunters do not wear hearing protection in the field because they want to hear their surroundings. The trouble is, exposure to even a single unsuppressed gunshot can, and often does, lead to permanent hearing damage. Suppressors allow hunters to maintain full situational awareness, while still protecting their hearing. The result is a safer hunting experience for the hunter, and for those nearby.NOISE COMPLAINTSAs urban developments advance into rural areas, shooting ranges and hunting preserves across the country are being closed due to noise complaints.ACCURACYOne of the most common problems for shooters is decreased accuracy caused by flinching in anticipation of the firearms discharge and recoil. By containing the explosion of the gunpowder at the muzzle, suppressors reduce recoil, and help decrease muzzle flinch. These benefits lead to improved accuracy, better shot placement, and more humane hunts.---How it works---1. Purchase the legal Solvent Trap that attaches to the end of your barrel of your rifle or pistol.2. Complete the Form 1 tax form and send the $200 tax to the ATF (https://johnpierceesq.com/the-complete-guide-to-the-new-form-1/)3. Wait until you get your Form 1 Tax Stamp Approval back from the ATF (Last I was told about 100 days)4. ONLY ONCE APPROVED - You can now modify and drill out the cone cups and the end cap to allow projectile to pass through the Solvent Trap (now legally a suppressor)5. Go shoot and notice the difference in sound!*It should be noted that Trump has vowed to remove Suppressors from this list that requires the $200 tax stamp fee, once that is done buying a suppressor will be like buying a shotgun - No tax.---Are suppressors legal?---Silencers are legal but are regulated by federal law and on a state-by-state basis by the Nation Firearm Act (NFA) branch of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives (BATFE). Private citizens can legally purchase and possess silencers in 42 states* without a permit.To purchase a silencer the following qualifications apply:• RESIDE IN ONE OF THE 42 STATES THAT CURRENTLY ALLOW CIVILIAN OWNERSHIP• BE A RESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES• BE LEGALLY ELIGIBLE TO PURCHASE A FIREARM• PASS A BATFE BACKGROUND CHECK• BE AT LEAST 21 YEARS OF AGE TO PURCHASE FROM A DEALER• BE AT LEAST 18 YEARS OF AGE TO PURCHASE FROM ANOTHER CITIZENhttps://www.thetruthaboutguns.com/2015/05/jeremy-s/nfa-for-beginners-form-1-to-manufacture-an-nfa-item/https://johnpierceesq.com/the-complete-guide-to-the-new-form-1/

postcontent: Heckler & Koch P7M10 with the beautiful factory nickel finish. These are great shooting pistols and were introduced in the early 1990’s. The P7M10, like the 9mm P7 models, is a fixed barrel, gas delayed, striker fired blowback pistol. They are of superb quality and craftsmanship. In my opinion, the P7 series pistols are the finest handguns HK ever built in their 50-year history. Accuracy is excellent, due to the 4” fixed barrel and the low bore axis makes them point very naturally. The P7M10 is the model that was brought onto the market for the then-new 40S&W cartridge. As the name would suggest, the magazine holds 10 rounds. In typical HK fashion, it was built to very high standards of excellence. This particular example was made in West Germany in 1992. It has the factory nickel finish and is in outstanding condition inside and out with a mint bore. I’ve owned the gun since 2008. I don’t shoot much 40S&W, so it was shot less than 200 rounds by me. It was perfectly reliable with minimal recoil. I have no idea how much it was shot prior to me owning it. Judging from the great condition, I would guess not too much. Both the steel and the grips are like new, This is perfect for the Heckler & Koch collector or German pistol collector. It’s also perfect for someone who wants a great shooting pistol for the range.
